1
00:02:36,440 --> 00:02:39,080
The hills are alive

2
00:02:39,320 --> 00:02:43,560
With the sound of music

3
00:02:43,800 --> 00:02:46,160
With songs they have sung

4
00:02:46,400 --> 00:02:51,080
For a thousand years

5
00:02:51,320 --> 00:02:54,360
The hills fill my heart

6
00:02:54,560 --> 00:02:58,960
With the sound of music

7
00:02:59,200 --> 00:03:06,080
My heart wants to sing
Every song it hears

8
00:03:06,560 --> 00:03:11,200
My heart wants to beat like the wings
Of the birds that rise

9
00:03:11,440 --> 00:03:14,400
From the lake to the trees

10
00:03:14,640 --> 00:03:18,760
My heart wants to sigh
Like a chime that flies

11
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:22,800
From a church on a breeze

12
00:03:23,040 --> 00:03:26,400
To laugh like a brook
When it trips and falls

13
00:03:26,640 --> 00:03:30,000
Over stones on its way

14
00:03:30,240 --> 00:03:33,960
To sing through the night

15
00:03:34,200 --> 00:03:37,840
Like a lark who is learning to pray

16
00:03:38,160 --> 00:03:43,520
I go to the hills

17
00:03:43,760 --> 00:03:49,680
When my heart is lonely

18
00:03:49,920 --> 00:03:53,640
I know I will hear

19
00:03:53,840 --> 00:03:58,160
What I've heard before

20
00:03:58,400 --> 00:04:02,960
My heart will be blessed

21
00:04:03,160 --> 00:04:10,680
With the sound of music

22
00:04:11,640 --> 00:04:16,560
And I'll sing...

23
00:04:16,800 --> 00:04:25,400
...once more

24
00:08:55,920 --> 00:09:00,680
Hallelujah, hallelujah

25
00:09:00,920 --> 00:09:05,360
Hallelujah, hallelujah

26
00:09:07,640 --> 00:09:09,560
-Reverend Mother.
-Sister Bernice.

27
00:09:09,800 --> 00:09:12,280
-I simply cannot find her.
-Maria?

28
00:09:13,360 --> 00:09:14,600
She's missing again.

29
00:09:15,440 --> 00:09:17,760
We should've put a cowbell
around her neck.

30
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:20,920
Have you tried the barn? You know
how much she adores the animals.

31
00:09:21,160 --> 00:09:23,800
I have looked everywhere.
In all of the usual places.

32
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:26,160
Sister, considering it's Maria. . .

33
00:09:26,400 --> 00:09:28,920
. . .I suggest you look in someplace
unusual.

34
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:35,200
Well, Reverend Mother. . .

35
00:09:35,440 --> 00:09:37,960
. . .I hope this new infraction ends
whatever doubts. . .

36
00:09:38,200 --> 00:09:41,320
. . .you may still have
about Maria's future here.

37
00:09:41,520 --> 00:09:45,400
I always try to keep faith
in my doubts, Sister Berthe.

38
00:09:45,640 --> 00:09:48,400
After all, the wool of a black sheep
is just as warm.

39
00:09:48,640 --> 00:09:52,760
We are not talking about sheep,
black or white, Sister Margaretta.

40
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:56,280
Of all the candidates for
the novitiate, Maria is the least--

41
00:09:56,520 --> 00:09:58,960
Children, children.

42
00:09:59,400 --> 00:10:03,200
We were speculating about
the qualifications of our postulants.

43
00:10:03,800 --> 00:10:06,680
The Mistress of Novices
and the Mistress of Postulants. . .

44
00:10:06,920 --> 00:10:12,000
. . .were trying to help me
by expressing opposite points of view.

45
00:10:12,240 --> 00:10:15,160
Tell me, Sister Catherine,
what do you think of Maria?

46
00:10:15,360 --> 00:10:18,320
She's a wonderful girl,
some of the time.

47
00:10:19,240 --> 00:10:22,200
-Sister Agatha?
-It's very easy to like Maria. . .

48
00:10:22,440 --> 00:10:24,880
. . .except when it's difficult.

49
00:10:25,120 --> 00:10:28,560
-And you, Sister Sophia?
-Oh, I love her very dearly.

50
00:10:28,760 --> 00:10:31,560
But she always seems to be
in trouble, doesn't she?

51
00:10:31,800 --> 00:10:33,480
Exactly what I say.

52
00:10:33,800 --> 00:10:36,160
She climbs a tree and scrapes her knee

53
00:10:36,360 --> 00:10:38,000
Her dress has got a tear

54
00:10:38,600 --> 00:10:42,600
She waltzes on her way to Mass
And whistles on the stair

55
00:10:43,240 --> 00:10:47,520
And underneath her wimple
She has curlers in her hair

56
00:10:47,800 --> 00:10:52,240
I've even heard her singing
ln the abbey

57
00:10:52,440 --> 00:10:54,360
She's always late for chapel

58
00:10:54,560 --> 00:10:56,760
But her penitence is real

59
00:10:57,040 --> 00:10:59,280
She's always late for everything

60
00:10:59,480 --> 00:11:01,440
Except for every meal

61
00:11:01,800 --> 00:11:06,320
I hate to have to say it
But I very firmly feel

62
00:11:06,520 --> 00:11:10,800
Maria 's not an asset to the abbey

63
00:11:11,240 --> 00:11:13,680
I'd like to say a word in her behalf

64
00:11:13,920 --> 00:11:15,200
Say it, Sister Margaretta.

65
00:11:16,040 --> 00:11:19,840
Maria makes me laugh

66
00:11:22,640 --> 00:11:26,360
How do you solve a problem like Maria?

67
00:11:26,600 --> 00:11:30,280
How do you catch a cloud
And pin it down?

68
00:11:30,520 --> 00:11:33,760
How do you find a word
That means Maria?

69
00:11:34,240 --> 00:11:35,320
A flibbertigibbet

70
00:11:35,520 --> 00:11:36,840
-A will-o '-the-wisp
-A clown

71
00:11:38,400 --> 00:11:42,000
Many a thing you know
You'd like to tell her

72
00:11:42,240 --> 00:11:45,520
Many a thing she ought to understand

73
00:11:45,960 --> 00:11:49,520
But how do you make her stay
And listen to all you say?

74
00:11:50,040 --> 00:11:53,400
How do you keep a wave upon the sand?

75
00:11:53,640 --> 00:11:57,520
How do you solve a problem like Maria?

76
00:11:58,040 --> 00:12:03,360
How do you hold a moonbeam...

77
00:12:03,560 --> 00:12:08,800
...in your hand?

78
00:12:09,840 --> 00:12:13,200
When I'm with her I'm confused
Out of focus and bemused

79
00:12:13,440 --> 00:12:16,760
And I never know exactly where I am

80
00:12:16,960 --> 00:12:20,160
-Unpredictable as weather
-She's as flighty as a feather

81
00:12:20,480 --> 00:12:22,240
-She's a darling
-She's a demon

82
00:12:22,440 --> 00:12:23,760
She's a lamb

83
00:12:24,120 --> 00:12:27,600
She'll out pester any pest
Drive a hornet from its nest

84
00:12:27,840 --> 00:12:31,000
She can throw a whirling dervish
Out of whirl

85
00:12:31,520 --> 00:12:34,960
-She is gentle, she is wild
-She's a riddle, she's a child

86
00:12:35,480 --> 00:12:37,960
-She's a headache
-She's an angel

87
00:12:38,160 --> 00:12:41,880
She's a girl

88
00:12:42,640 --> 00:12:46,360
How do you solve a problem like Maria?

89
00:12:46,560 --> 00:12:50,160
How do you catch a cloud
And pin it down?

90
00:12:50,400 --> 00:12:53,800
How do you find a word
That means Maria?

91
00:12:54,040 --> 00:12:55,960
-A flibbertigibbet
-A will-o '-the-wisp

92
00:12:56,160 --> 00:12:57,760
A clown

93
00:12:58,200 --> 00:13:01,800
Many a thing you know
You'd like to tell her

94
00:13:02,040 --> 00:13:05,360
Many a thing she ought to understand

95
00:13:05,560 --> 00:13:09,760
-But how do you make her stay
-And listen to all you say?

96
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:13,920
How do you keep a wave upon the sand?

97
00:13:14,120 --> 00:13:19,720
How do you solve a problem like Maria?

98
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:41,520
How do you hold a moonbeam...

99
00:13:42,320 --> 00:13:48,520
...in your hand?

100
00:13:59,840 --> 00:14:01,760
You may go in now, Maria.

101
00:14:13,840 --> 00:14:15,400
Come here, my child.

102
00:14:21,640 --> 00:14:22,960
Now sit down.

103
00:14:23,840 --> 00:14:27,280
Reverend Mother, I'm sorry.
I couldn't help myself.

104
00:14:27,520 --> 00:14:30,320
-The hills were beckoning and before--
-Dear.

105
00:14:30,760 --> 00:14:32,640
I haven't summoned you for apologies.

106
00:14:32,880 --> 00:14:35,000
Please let me ask for forgiveness.

107
00:14:35,640 --> 00:14:36,840
If you'll feel better.

108
00:14:37,720 --> 00:14:40,000
Yes, you see,
the sky was so blue today. . .

109
00:14:40,240 --> 00:14:43,880
. . .and everything was so green and
fragrant, I had to be a part of it.

110
00:14:44,120 --> 00:14:48,400
The Untersberg led me higher like
it wanted me to go through the clouds.

111
00:14:48,600 --> 00:14:50,640
Suppose darkness had come
and you were lost?

112
00:14:50,840 --> 00:14:53,000
Mother, I could never be lost
up there.

113
00:14:53,240 --> 00:14:55,960
That's my mountain.
I was brought up on it.

114
00:14:56,160 --> 00:14:58,360
It was the mountain that led me
to you.

115
00:14:59,120 --> 00:15:01,960
When I was a child,
I would come down and climb a tree. . .

116
00:15:02,200 --> 00:15:03,920
. . .and look in your garden.

117
00:15:04,120 --> 00:15:06,960
I'd see the sisters at work
and hear them sing.

118
00:15:08,240 --> 00:15:11,720
Which brings me to another
transgression, Reverend Mother.

119
00:15:11,920 --> 00:15:14,000
I was singing out there today.

120
00:15:14,600 --> 00:15:18,480
Only in the abbey do we have rules
about postulants singing.

121
00:15:18,680 --> 00:15:20,600
I can't stop wherever I am.

122
00:15:20,840 --> 00:15:23,080
Worse, I can't seem to stop
saying things.

123
00:15:23,320 --> 00:15:25,480
Everything I think and feel.

124
00:15:25,720 --> 00:15:27,120
Some call that "honesty. "

125
00:15:27,320 --> 00:15:29,600
Oh, but it's terrible,
Reverend Mother!

126
00:15:29,840 --> 00:15:33,560
You know how Sister Berthe makes me
kiss the floor after a disagreement?

127
00:15:33,920 --> 00:15:37,280
Lately, I kiss the floor
when I see her coming to save time.

128
00:15:39,840 --> 00:15:40,960
Maria. . .

129
00:15:41,920 --> 00:15:44,800
. . .when you saw us over the wall
and longed to be with us. . .

130
00:15:45,040 --> 00:15:49,560
. . .that didn't mean you were prepared
for the way we live here, did it?

131
00:15:50,840 --> 00:15:53,160
No, Mother, but I pray and I try.

132
00:15:53,360 --> 00:15:55,000
And I am learning. I really am.

133
00:15:55,240 --> 00:15:57,800
What is the most important lesson
you have learned here?

134
00:15:58,440 --> 00:16:02,080
To find out what is the will of God
and do it wholeheartedly.

135
00:16:04,800 --> 00:16:05,880
Maria. . .

136
00:16:07,320 --> 00:16:10,000
. . .it seems to be God's will
that you leave us.

137
00:16:10,240 --> 00:16:11,680
-Leave?
-Only for a while.

138
00:16:12,160 --> 00:16:14,400
No, Mother!
Please don't send me away!

139
00:16:14,640 --> 00:16:18,720
This is where I belong. It's my home,
my family. It's my life.

140
00:16:19,360 --> 00:16:22,240
-Are you truly ready for it?
-Yes, I am.

141
00:16:22,440 --> 00:16:27,160
If you go out into the world for a
time, knowing what we expect of you. . .

142
00:16:27,400 --> 00:16:30,040
. . .you will find out
if you can expect it of yourself.

143
00:16:30,240 --> 00:16:34,360
I know what you expect, Mother,
and I can do it! I promise I can!

144
00:16:37,760 --> 00:16:38,960
Yes, Mother.

145
00:16:40,960 --> 00:16:42,560
If it is God's will.

146
00:16:44,720 --> 00:16:49,600
There is a family near Salzburg that
needs a governess until September.

147
00:16:49,840 --> 00:16:51,960
-September?
-For seven children.

148
00:16:52,560 --> 00:16:53,560
Seven children?!

149
00:16:53,800 --> 00:16:55,000
Do you like children?

150
00:16:55,760 --> 00:16:57,480
Well, yes, but seven!

151
00:16:58,600 --> 00:17:01,640
I will tell Captain von Trapp
to expect you tomorrow.

152
00:17:02,160 --> 00:17:03,440
Captain?

153
00:17:04,160 --> 00:17:08,800
A retired officer of the lmperial
Navy. A fine man and a brave one.

154
00:17:09,040 --> 00:17:11,640
His wife died,
and he is alone with the children.

155
00:17:11,840 --> 00:17:15,960
I understand he has had a difficult
time keeping a governess there.

156
00:17:16,720 --> 00:17:18,920
Why difficult, Reverend Mother?

157
00:17:20,240 --> 00:17:23,040
The Lord will show you
in His own good time.

158
00:17:58,360 --> 00:18:00,760
When the Lord closes a door. . .

159
00:18:00,960 --> 00:18:03,360
. . .somewhere He opens a window.

160
00:18:05,640 --> 00:18:10,400
What will this day be like?

161
00:18:10,640 --> 00:18:12,760
I wonder

162
00:18:19,000 --> 00:18:22,960
What will my future be?

163
00:18:23,760 --> 00:18:25,920
I wonder

164
00:18:27,440 --> 00:18:30,360
It could be so exciting

165
00:18:30,560 --> 00:18:33,560
To be out in the world
To be free

166
00:18:33,760 --> 00:18:36,720
My heart should be wildly rejoicing

167
00:18:37,840 --> 00:18:42,960
Oh, what's the matter with me?

168
00:18:43,280 --> 00:18:46,200
I've always longed for adventure

169
00:18:46,440 --> 00:18:49,880
To do the things I've never dared

170
00:18:50,120 --> 00:18:53,200
Now here I'm facing adventure

171
00:18:53,440 --> 00:18:59,320
Then why am I so scared?

172
00:19:02,640 --> 00:19:05,400
A captain with seven children

173
00:19:05,640 --> 00:19:08,360
What's so fearsome about that?

174
00:19:10,800 --> 00:19:13,280
I must stop these doubts and worries

175
00:19:13,520 --> 00:19:16,280
If I don 't ljust know I'll turn back

176
00:19:16,520 --> 00:19:19,560
I must dream of the things
I am seeking

177
00:19:20,560 --> 00:19:25,360
I am seeking the courage I lack

178
00:19:26,280 --> 00:19:29,960
The courage to serve them
With reliance

179
00:19:30,200 --> 00:19:33,000
Face my mistakes without defiance

180
00:19:33,240 --> 00:19:34,880
Show them I'm worthy

181
00:19:35,120 --> 00:19:37,680
And while I show them

182
00:19:37,920 --> 00:19:41,560
I'll show me

183
00:19:41,760 --> 00:19:46,960
So let them bring on
All their problems

184
00:19:47,160 --> 00:19:50,280
I'll do better than my best

185
00:19:50,520 --> 00:19:53,480
I have confidence
They'll put me to the test

186
00:19:53,720 --> 00:19:57,040
But I'll make them see
I have confidence in me

187
00:19:57,240 --> 00:20:00,400
Somehow I will impress them

188
00:20:00,640 --> 00:20:03,760
I will be firm but kind

189
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:07,160
And all those children
Heaven bless them

190
00:20:07,400 --> 00:20:10,560
They will look up to me
And mind me

191
00:20:10,800 --> 00:20:13,800
With each step I am more certain

192
00:20:14,040 --> 00:20:17,160
Everything will turn out fine

193
00:20:17,360 --> 00:20:20,360
I have confidence
The world can all be mine

194
00:20:20,560 --> 00:20:25,840
They'll have to agree
I have confidence in me

195
00:20:27,320 --> 00:20:29,960
I have confidence in sunshine

196
00:20:30,200 --> 00:20:33,160
I have confidence in rain

197
00:20:33,360 --> 00:20:36,160
I have confidence
That spring will come again

198
00:20:36,400 --> 00:20:39,360
Besides which you see
I have confidence in me

199
00:20:39,600 --> 00:20:42,600
Strength doesn 't lie in numbers

200
00:20:42,840 --> 00:20:45,760
Strength doesn 't lie in wealth

201
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:49,160
Strength lies in nights
Ofpeaceful slumbers

202
00:20:49,400 --> 00:20:52,200
When you wake up, wake up
It's healthy

203
00:20:52,440 --> 00:20:55,360
All I trust I leave my heart to

204
00:20:55,560 --> 00:20:58,360
All I trust becomes my own

205
00:20:58,560 --> 00:21:03,160
I have confidence in confidence alone

206
00:21:17,200 --> 00:21:18,760
Oh, help.

207
00:21:30,440 --> 00:21:36,840
I have confidence in confidence alone

208
00:21:37,560 --> 00:21:42,200
Besides which you see
I have confidence...

209
00:21:42,440 --> 00:21:49,000
...in me

210
00:21:55,280 --> 00:21:57,560
Hello. Here I am.

211
00:22:00,240 --> 00:22:02,040
I'm from the convent.
I'm the new governess, captain.

212
00:22:03,640 --> 00:22:06,760
And I'm the old butler, fräulein.

213
00:22:08,600 --> 00:22:10,360
Well, how do you do?

214
00:22:20,440 --> 00:22:24,360
You'll wait here, please.

215
00:23:47,160 --> 00:23:51,120
In future, remember certain rooms
in this house are not to be disturbed.

216
00:23:52,200 --> 00:23:53,640
Yes, captain, sir.

217
00:24:01,200 --> 00:24:06,240
-Why do you stare at me that way?
-You don't look like a sea captain.

218
00:24:07,440 --> 00:24:10,360
I'm afraid you don't look
very much like a governess.

219
00:24:11,040 --> 00:24:12,080
-Turn around.
-What?

220
00:24:12,400 --> 00:24:13,560
Turn.

221
00:24:16,640 --> 00:24:17,760
Hat off.

222
00:24:20,840 --> 00:24:23,360
Put on another dress
before meeting the children.

223
00:24:23,600 --> 00:24:25,160
But I don't have another.

224
00:24:25,400 --> 00:24:28,160
When we enter the abbey,
our worldly clothes go to the poor.

225
00:24:28,400 --> 00:24:29,560
What about this one?

226
00:24:29,800 --> 00:24:31,080
The poor didn't want it.

227
00:24:32,840 --> 00:24:36,200
There wasn't time to make a new dress.
I can make clothes.

228
00:24:37,400 --> 00:24:39,560
I'll see that you get some material.

229
00:24:40,240 --> 00:24:41,760
Today, if possible.

230
00:24:42,720 --> 00:24:44,400
-Now, fräulein. . . .
-Maria.

231
00:24:44,640 --> 00:24:47,200
I don't know how much
the abbess told you.

232
00:24:47,440 --> 00:24:49,960
You are the twelfth governess. . .

233
00:24:50,160 --> 00:24:52,520
. . .to look after my children
since their mother died.

234
00:24:52,720 --> 00:24:54,840
I trust you will be an improvement
on the last one.

235
00:24:55,080 --> 00:24:56,840
She stayed only two hours.

236
00:24:58,480 --> 00:25:00,960
What's wrong with the children, sir?

237
00:25:02,360 --> 00:25:06,560
Nothing is wrong with the children,
only the governesses.

238
00:25:06,840 --> 00:25:11,560
They could not maintain discipline,
without which the house cannot be run.

239
00:25:12,440 --> 00:25:14,200
Drill them in their studies.

240
00:25:14,440 --> 00:25:17,800
I will not permit them to dream
away their summer holidays.

241
00:25:18,040 --> 00:25:20,600
Each afternoon,
they march, breathing deeply.

242
00:25:20,840 --> 00:25:22,400
Bedtime is to be strictly observed.

243
00:25:22,640 --> 00:25:23,560
When do they play?

244
00:25:23,760 --> 00:25:27,640
You will see to it that they conduct
themselves with the utmost decorum.

245
00:25:27,880 --> 00:25:30,720
-I am placing you in command.
-Yes, sir.

246
00:26:48,040 --> 00:26:49,160
Now. . .

247
00:26:49,720 --> 00:26:52,560
. . .this is your new governess,
Fräulein Maria.

248
00:26:54,160 --> 00:26:56,080
Give your name at your signal.

249
00:26:56,360 --> 00:27:00,360
Fräulein, listen carefully. Learn
their signals so you can call them.

250
00:27:01,600 --> 00:27:02,960
Liesl.

251
00:27:03,200 --> 00:27:04,880
Friedrich.

252
00:27:05,120 --> 00:27:06,600
Louisa.

253
00:27:06,840 --> 00:27:08,080
Kurt.

254
00:27:08,280 --> 00:27:09,280
Brigitta.

255
00:27:09,520 --> 00:27:10,760
Marta.

256
00:27:16,880 --> 00:27:18,160
Gretl.

257
00:27:22,600 --> 00:27:25,880
Now, let's see how well you listened.

258
00:27:26,120 --> 00:27:28,400
I won't need to whistle for them,
Reverend Captain.

259
00:27:28,640 --> 00:27:31,960
I mean, I'll use their names.
Such lovely names.

260
00:27:32,160 --> 00:27:35,200
Fräulein, this is a large house.
The grounds are extensive.

261
00:27:35,440 --> 00:27:38,080
And I will not have anyone shouting.

262
00:27:38,320 --> 00:27:39,960
You will take this, please.
Learn to use it.

263
00:27:40,160 --> 00:27:41,760
The children will help you.

264
00:27:43,720 --> 00:27:47,560
Now, when I want you,
this is what you will hear.

265
00:27:48,360 --> 00:27:50,120
Oh, no, sir. I'm sorry, sir!

266
00:27:50,960 --> 00:27:52,400
I could never answer to a whistle.

267
00:27:52,640 --> 00:27:55,160
Whistles are for animals,
not for children.

268
00:27:55,400 --> 00:27:57,360
And definitely not for me.

269
00:27:57,600 --> 00:28:00,160
It would be too humiliating.

270
00:28:00,920 --> 00:28:05,920
Fräulein, were you this much trouble
at the abbey?

271
00:28:06,200 --> 00:28:07,280
Oh, much more, sir.

272
00:28:17,920 --> 00:28:19,440
I don't know your signal.

273
00:28:20,840 --> 00:28:23,360
You may call me "captain. "

274
00:28:35,760 --> 00:28:37,160
At ease.

275
00:28:39,840 --> 00:28:41,360
Now that there's just us. . .

276
00:28:41,560 --> 00:28:45,560
. . .would you please tell me all your
names again and how old you are.

277
00:28:46,040 --> 00:28:49,880
I'm Liesl. I'm 1 6 years old,
and I don't need a governess.

278
00:28:50,600 --> 00:28:53,560
I'm glad you told me, Liesl.
We'll just be good friends.

279
00:28:55,600 --> 00:28:59,280
I'm Friedrich. I'm 1 4.
I'm impossible.

280
00:28:59,520 --> 00:29:01,160
Really? Who told you that, Friedrich?

281
00:29:01,360 --> 00:29:04,760
Fräulein Josephine.
Four governesses ago.

282
00:29:05,160 --> 00:29:06,560
I'm Brigitta.

283
00:29:08,320 --> 00:29:12,160
You didn't tell me how old you are,
Louisa.

284
00:29:12,840 --> 00:29:15,000
I'm Brigitta. She's Louisa.

285
00:29:15,240 --> 00:29:17,880
She's 1 3 years old, and you're smart.

286
00:29:18,120 --> 00:29:21,720
I'm 1 0, and I think your dress
is the ugliest one I ever saw.

287
00:29:22,040 --> 00:29:24,560
-Brigitta, you shouldn't say that.
-Why not?

288
00:29:24,760 --> 00:29:26,960
-Don't you think it's ugly?
-Of course.

289
00:29:27,200 --> 00:29:29,800
But Fräulein Helga's was ugliest.

290
00:29:30,040 --> 00:29:32,560
I'm Kurt. I'm 1 1 .
I'm incorrigible.

291
00:29:32,800 --> 00:29:35,800
-Congratulations.
-What's "incorrigible"?

292
00:29:36,040 --> 00:29:39,760
I think it means you want
to be treated like a boy.

293
00:29:41,840 --> 00:29:45,000
I'm Marta, and I'm going to be
seven on Tuesday.

294
00:29:45,240 --> 00:29:46,560
I'd like a pink parasol.

295
00:29:47,720 --> 00:29:49,200
Pink's my favorite color too.

296
00:29:51,440 --> 00:29:52,560
Yes, you're Gretl.

297
00:29:53,440 --> 00:29:55,120
And you're five years old?

298
00:29:55,520 --> 00:29:57,440
My, you're practically a lady.

299
00:29:59,840 --> 00:30:02,760
I have to tell you a secret.
I've never been a governess.

300
00:30:04,120 --> 00:30:06,800
You don't know anything
about being a governess?

301
00:30:07,040 --> 00:30:08,360
Nothing. I'll need lots of advice.

302
00:30:09,240 --> 00:30:13,600
The best way to start is to tell
Father to mind his own business.

303
00:30:13,840 --> 00:30:15,560
Never come to dinner on time.

304
00:30:15,760 --> 00:30:17,960
Never eat your soup quietly.

305
00:30:18,640 --> 00:30:20,600
During dessert, always blow your nose.

306
00:30:20,840 --> 00:30:23,480
Don't you believe a word they say,
Fräulein Maria.

307
00:30:23,720 --> 00:30:26,960
-Oh, why not?
-Because I like you.

308
00:30:27,720 --> 00:30:29,600
Children, outside for your walk.

309
00:30:29,840 --> 00:30:31,600
Father's orders. Hurry up.

310
00:30:31,840 --> 00:30:33,080
Quick, quick, quick.

311
00:30:33,320 --> 00:30:36,400
Fräulein Maria, I'm Frau Schmidt,
the housekeeper.

312
00:30:36,640 --> 00:30:37,600
How do you do.

313
00:30:37,840 --> 00:30:40,560
I'll show you to your room.
Follow me.

314
00:30:51,240 --> 00:30:52,920
Poor little dears.

315
00:31:05,120 --> 00:31:09,280
You're very lucky. With
Fräulein Helga it was a snake.

316
00:31:22,640 --> 00:31:23,880
Good evening.

317
00:31:25,240 --> 00:31:28,680
-Good evening, children.
-Good evening, Fräulein Maria.

318
00:31:35,560 --> 00:31:37,160
Enchanting little ritual.

319
00:31:37,360 --> 00:31:39,960
Something you learned at the abbey?

320
00:31:41,120 --> 00:31:43,320
No.

321
00:31:44,920 --> 00:31:46,160
Rheumatism.

322
00:31:55,520 --> 00:31:58,560
Excuse me, captain. Haven't we
forgotten to thank the Lord?

323
00:32:06,440 --> 00:32:09,320
For what we receive,
may the Lord make us truly thankful.

324
00:32:09,840 --> 00:32:11,680
-Amen.
-Amen.

325
00:32:16,040 --> 00:32:17,880
I'd like to thank you all. . .

326
00:32:18,080 --> 00:32:20,960
. . .for the precious gift
you left in my pocket today.

327
00:32:24,280 --> 00:32:26,040
What gift?

328
00:32:29,040 --> 00:32:31,120
It's a secret between
the children and me.

329
00:32:31,320 --> 00:32:34,840
Then I suggest you keep it,
and let us eat.

330
00:32:35,200 --> 00:32:37,080
Knowing how nervous
I must have been. . .

331
00:32:37,320 --> 00:32:39,640
. . .a stranger in a new household. . .

332
00:32:39,840 --> 00:32:42,800
. . .knowing how important it was
for me to feel accepted. . .

333
00:32:43,040 --> 00:32:47,080
. . .it was so kind and thoughtful of
you to make my first moments here. . .

334
00:32:47,280 --> 00:32:49,400
. . .so warm and happy. . .

335
00:32:49,640 --> 00:32:51,320
. . .and pleasant.

336
00:33:00,200 --> 00:33:02,160
-What is the matter, Marta?
-Nothing.

337
00:33:14,040 --> 00:33:15,040
Fräulein. . .

338
00:33:15,280 --> 00:33:18,960
. . .is it to be at every meal
or merely at dinnertime. . .

339
00:33:19,160 --> 00:33:23,560
. . .that you intend leading us through
this rare and wonderful new world. . .

340
00:33:23,760 --> 00:33:25,360
. . .of indigestion?

341
00:33:26,840 --> 00:33:29,560
They're all right, captain.
They're just happy.

342
00:33:47,560 --> 00:33:50,160
-Rolf, good evening.
-Good evening, Franz.

343
00:33:50,400 --> 00:33:53,040
-I trust everything is under control?
-Yes, yes.

344
00:33:54,560 --> 00:33:56,920
-Are there any developments?
-Perhaps.

345
00:33:57,120 --> 00:33:59,200
-Is the captain home?
-He's at dinner.

346
00:33:59,440 --> 00:34:01,680
-With the family?
-Yes.

347
00:34:01,920 --> 00:34:03,600
Give him this telegram at once.

348
00:34:04,360 --> 00:34:05,360
Certainly.

349
00:34:16,560 --> 00:34:18,240
A telegram for you, sir.

350
00:34:20,960 --> 00:34:22,720
Franz? Who delivered it?

351
00:34:23,000 --> 00:34:24,960
That young lad Rolf, of course.

352
00:34:27,200 --> 00:34:28,880
Father, may I be excused?

353
00:34:29,800 --> 00:34:34,080
Children, in the morning I shall
be going to Vienna.

354
00:34:34,360 --> 00:34:36,720
Not again, Father!

355
00:34:40,440 --> 00:34:42,400
How long will you be gone this time?

356
00:34:43,040 --> 00:34:44,400
I'm not sure, Gretl.

357
00:34:44,640 --> 00:34:48,080
-To visit Baroness Schraeder again?
-Mind your own business!

358
00:34:49,000 --> 00:34:50,840
As a matter of fact, yes, Louisa.

359
00:34:52,560 --> 00:34:56,240
-Why can't we ever see the baroness?
-Why would she want to see you?

360
00:34:56,480 --> 00:35:01,200
You are going to see the baroness.
I'm bringing her back with me to visit.

361
00:35:02,640 --> 00:35:04,320
And Uncle Max.

362
00:35:04,560 --> 00:35:06,920
Uncle Max!

363
00:35:22,320 --> 00:35:23,560
Rolf!

364
00:35:26,520 --> 00:35:27,520
Oh, Rolf!

365
00:35:30,000 --> 00:35:32,800
-No, Liesl. We mustn't!
-Why not, silly?

366
00:35:33,040 --> 00:35:35,560
-I don't know--
-Isn't this why you're waiting?

367
00:35:35,800 --> 00:35:37,560
Yes, of course.

368
00:35:37,800 --> 00:35:40,480
-I've missed you, Liesl.
-You have? How much?

369
00:35:40,720 --> 00:35:44,400
I even thought of sending a telegram,
so I'd be able to deliver it here.

370
00:35:44,640 --> 00:35:48,360
Oh, that's a lovely thought!
Why don't you, right now?

371
00:35:48,600 --> 00:35:52,600
-But I'm here!
-Please, Rolf. Send me a telegram.

372
00:35:52,840 --> 00:35:56,160
I'll start it for you.
"Dear Liesl. . . . "

373
00:35:56,800 --> 00:36:00,280
"Dear Liesl: I'd like to be able
to tell you. . .

374
00:36:00,480 --> 00:36:02,600
. . .how I feel about you. Stop.

375
00:36:02,840 --> 00:36:07,200
Unfortunately, this wire
is already too expensive.

376
00:36:07,400 --> 00:36:08,760
Sincerely, Rolf. "

377
00:36:08,960 --> 00:36:11,600
-"Sincerely"?
-Cordially.

378
00:36:11,800 --> 00:36:14,360
-"Cordially"?
-Affectionately?

379
00:36:16,600 --> 00:36:18,560
Will there be any reply?

380
00:36:19,800 --> 00:36:21,880
"Dear Rolf: Stop.

381
00:36:22,840 --> 00:36:25,840
Don't stop! Your Liesl. "

382
00:36:27,440 --> 00:36:31,160
If only we didn't have to wait
for someone to send Father a telegram.

383
00:36:31,400 --> 00:36:33,720
How do I know when I'll see you again?

384
00:36:34,560 --> 00:36:35,760
Well, let's see. . . .

385
00:36:38,640 --> 00:36:40,480
I could come here by mistake.

386
00:36:41,440 --> 00:36:45,920
With a telegram for Colonel Schneider!
He's here from Berlin staying with--

387
00:36:46,800 --> 00:36:49,960
No one knows he's here.
Don't tell your father.

388
00:36:50,200 --> 00:36:53,240
-Why not?
-Your father's so Austrian.

389
00:36:53,440 --> 00:36:54,680
We're all Austrian.

390
00:36:54,880 --> 00:36:59,120
Some think we ought to be German, and
they're very mad at those who don't.

391
00:36:59,320 --> 00:37:01,040
They're getting ready to--

392
00:37:02,640 --> 00:37:04,960
Let's hope your father
doesn't get into trouble.

393
00:37:05,200 --> 00:37:09,960
Don't worry. He's a big naval hero.
He was even decorated by the emperor.

394
00:37:10,160 --> 00:37:13,280
I don't worry about him.
I worry about his daughter.

395
00:37:13,800 --> 00:37:15,200
Me? Why?

396
00:37:15,440 --> 00:37:17,000
-Well, you're so--
-What?

397
00:37:17,360 --> 00:37:18,840
You're such a baby!

398
00:37:19,240 --> 00:37:22,040
I'm 1 6.
What's such a baby about that?

399
00:37:24,200 --> 00:37:27,560
You wait, little girl
On an empty stage

400
00:37:27,800 --> 00:37:31,040
For fate to turn the light on

401
00:37:31,640 --> 00:37:34,760
Your life, little girl
ls an empty page

402
00:37:35,000 --> 00:37:38,920
That men will want to write on

403
00:37:39,600 --> 00:37:44,880
To write on

404
00:37:45,760 --> 00:37:49,520
You are 16 going on 17

405
00:37:49,720 --> 00:37:53,360
Baby, it's time to think

406
00:37:53,560 --> 00:37:57,080
Better beware
Be canny and careful

407
00:37:57,320 --> 00:38:00,800
Baby, you're on the brink

408
00:38:01,120 --> 00:38:04,800
You are 16 going on 17

409
00:38:05,000 --> 00:38:08,480
Fellows will fall in line

410
00:38:08,800 --> 00:38:12,000
Eager young lads
And roués and cads

411
00:38:12,200 --> 00:38:15,960
Will offer you food and wine

412
00:38:16,200 --> 00:38:19,840
Totally unprepared are you

413
00:38:20,240 --> 00:38:23,640
To face a world of men

414
00:38:24,200 --> 00:38:28,200
Timid and shy and scared are you

415
00:38:28,440 --> 00:38:31,840
Of things beyond your ken

416
00:38:32,040 --> 00:38:35,760
You need someone older and wiser

417
00:38:35,960 --> 00:38:39,680
Telling you what to do

418
00:38:39,920 --> 00:38:43,200
I am 17 going on 18

419
00:38:43,440 --> 00:38:49,160
I'll take care of you

420
00:39:20,320 --> 00:39:23,560
I am 16 going on 17

421
00:39:23,760 --> 00:39:27,000
I know that I'm naive

422
00:39:27,240 --> 00:39:30,360
Fellows I meet
May tell me I'm sweet

423
00:39:30,560 --> 00:39:34,160
And willingly I believe

424
00:39:34,560 --> 00:39:37,600
I am 16 going on 17

425
00:39:37,840 --> 00:39:41,440
Innocent as a rose

426
00:39:41,640 --> 00:39:44,960
Bachelor dandies
Drinkers of brandies

427
00:39:45,200 --> 00:39:48,400
What do I know of those?

428
00:39:48,640 --> 00:39:52,040
Totally unprepared am I

429
00:39:52,240 --> 00:39:55,600
To face a world of men

430
00:39:56,040 --> 00:39:59,200
Timid and shy and scared am I

431
00:39:59,440 --> 00:40:03,000
Of things beyond my ken

432
00:40:03,440 --> 00:40:06,880
I need someone older and wiser

433
00:40:07,120 --> 00:40:10,280
Telling me what to do

434
00:40:10,640 --> 00:40:14,160
You are 17 going on 18

435
00:40:14,360 --> 00:40:19,800
I'll depend on you

436
00:42:08,240 --> 00:42:09,560
Come in.

437
00:42:10,560 --> 00:42:12,160
Frau Schmidt.

438
00:42:14,360 --> 00:42:16,080
For your new dresses.

439
00:42:16,320 --> 00:42:20,200
-The captain had these sent from town.
-Oh, how lovely!

440
00:42:20,440 --> 00:42:23,760
These will make the prettiest
clothes I've ever had.

441
00:42:24,000 --> 00:42:27,360
Do you think he would
get me more material if I asked?

442
00:42:27,600 --> 00:42:31,080
-How many dresses do you need?
-Not for me, for the children.

443
00:42:31,320 --> 00:42:33,320
I want to make them some play clothes.

444
00:42:33,520 --> 00:42:36,960
The von Trapp children don't play.
They march.

445
00:42:37,400 --> 00:42:39,760
Surely you don't approve of that.

446
00:42:40,720 --> 00:42:43,000
Ever since the captain
lost his poor wife. . .

447
00:42:43,240 --> 00:42:45,840
. . .he runs this house as if on
one of his ships.

448
00:42:46,640 --> 00:42:47,960
Whistles, orders.

449
00:42:48,200 --> 00:42:50,000
No more music, no more laughing.

450
00:42:50,240 --> 00:42:53,600
Nothing that reminds him of her.
Even the children.

451
00:42:54,120 --> 00:42:55,160
But that's so wrong.

452
00:42:55,960 --> 00:42:57,400
Oh, well.

453
00:42:57,640 --> 00:43:01,160
How do you like your room?
There'll be new drapes at the windows.

454
00:43:01,400 --> 00:43:02,600
Bu these are fine.

455
00:43:02,840 --> 00:43:04,400
New ones have been ordered.

456
00:43:04,600 --> 00:43:07,800
-But I really don't need them.
-Good night, now.

457
00:43:08,040 --> 00:43:11,920
Frau Schmidt, if I asked
the captain about the material. . .?

458
00:43:12,160 --> 00:43:16,400
-He's leaving in the morning.
-Of course. How long will he be gone?

459
00:43:17,000 --> 00:43:21,400
It depends. The last time he visited
the baroness, he stayed for a month.

460
00:43:22,520 --> 00:43:26,920
I shouldn't be saying this to you.
I don't know you that well.

461
00:43:27,160 --> 00:43:29,960
But if you ask me,
the captain's thinking seriously. . .

462
00:43:30,160 --> 00:43:32,320
. . .of marrying her before
summer's over.

463
00:43:32,520 --> 00:43:35,640
Wonderful! The children will
have a mother again.

464
00:43:37,040 --> 00:43:38,280
Yes.

465
00:43:38,520 --> 00:43:40,200
Well, good night.

466
00:43:40,400 --> 00:43:41,760
Good night.

467
00:43:59,400 --> 00:44:02,160
Dear Father, now I know
why You sent me here.

468
00:44:02,360 --> 00:44:05,120
To help these children
prepare for a new mother.

469
00:44:05,360 --> 00:44:08,520
And I pray this will become
a happy family in Thy sight.

470
00:44:08,720 --> 00:44:11,720
God bless the captain.
God bless Liesl and Friedrich.

471
00:44:11,920 --> 00:44:15,920
God bless Louisa, Brigitta,
Marta and little Gretl.

472
00:44:16,200 --> 00:44:18,920
And I forgot the other boy.
What's his name?

473
00:44:20,560 --> 00:44:22,320
Well, God bless what's-his-name.

474
00:44:22,520 --> 00:44:26,440
God bless the Reverend Mother
and Sister Margaretta. . .

475
00:44:26,640 --> 00:44:28,320
. . .and everybody at the abbey.

476
00:44:28,520 --> 00:44:30,960
And now, dear God, about Liesl.

477
00:44:31,400 --> 00:44:33,200
Help her know that I'm her friend. . .

478
00:44:33,400 --> 00:44:35,920
. . .and help her tell me
what she's been up to.

479
00:44:36,560 --> 00:44:37,720
Are you going to tell on me?

480
00:44:37,960 --> 00:44:41,240
Help me to be understanding
so I may guide her footsteps.

481
00:44:41,480 --> 00:44:44,040
In the name of the Father,
the Son and the Holy Ghost.

482
00:44:44,240 --> 00:44:47,120
I was out walking
and somebody locked the doors early.

483
00:44:47,360 --> 00:44:50,880
I didn't want to wake everybody,
so when I saw your window open. . . .

484
00:44:52,400 --> 00:44:55,360
You're not going to tell Father,
are you?

485
00:45:01,200 --> 00:45:02,440
How did you climb up?

486
00:45:02,920 --> 00:45:05,920
It's how we always got in
to play tricks on the governess.

487
00:45:06,120 --> 00:45:09,000
Louisa can make it with
a whole jar of spiders in her hand.

488
00:45:09,960 --> 00:45:11,520
Spiders?

489
00:45:15,120 --> 00:45:17,640
Were you out walking all by yourself?

490
00:45:24,800 --> 00:45:28,320
If we wash that dress tonight,
nobody would notice it tomorrow.

491
00:45:29,000 --> 00:45:30,720
You could put this on.

492
00:45:32,360 --> 00:45:34,960
Take your dress and put it
to soak in the bathtub.

493
00:45:35,160 --> 00:45:38,520
Come back here and sit on the bed,
and we'll have a talk.

494
00:45:39,800 --> 00:45:42,720
I told you today
I didn't need a governess.

495
00:45:42,920 --> 00:45:44,920
Well, maybe I do.

496
00:46:14,160 --> 00:46:16,560
Gretl, are you scared?

497
00:46:19,960 --> 00:46:22,160
You're not frightened
of a storm, are you?

498
00:46:22,360 --> 00:46:24,520
You just stay right here with me.

499
00:46:25,680 --> 00:46:29,720
-Where are the others?
-They're asleep. They're not scared.

500
00:46:33,960 --> 00:46:35,720
Oh, no? Look.

